{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"de898658-c56c-4de3-9d92-7dee41970ceb","content":"Yes, you'll hit **target framework compatibility issues**. MSTest v3 dropped support for end-of-life runtimes. Your project targets three frameworks, and **two are problematic**:\n\n| Target | MSTest v3 Support |\n|---|---|\n| `net462` | ✅ Supported |\n| `net5.0` | ❌ Dropped (EOL) |\n| `netcoreapp3.1` | ❌ Dropped (EOL) |\n\nMSTest v3 requires **.NET Framework 4.6.2+** or **.NET 6.0+**.\n\n**To migrate**, you'd need to update your TFMs, e.g. replace `net5.0` → `net6.0` (or `net8.0`) and `netcoreapp3.1` → `net6.0`. You can also simplify to the single `MSTest` meta-package instead of separate `TestFramework`/`TestAdapter` references.\n\nWant me to update the project file for MSTest v3?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"65b4886c-6cba-414b-a1cc-fbd34b069616","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user's project targets `net5.0`, `net462`, and `netcoreapp3.1`. They want to migrate from MSTest v2 (2.2.10) to MSTest v3.\n\nMSTest v3 has some important compatibility changes:\n\n1. **Framework support**: MSTest v3 dropped support for older frameworks. Specifically:\n   - `.NET 5.0` is no longer supported (it's out of support from Microsoft)\n   - `netcoreapp3.1` is no longer supported (also out of support)\n   - `.NET Framework 4.6.2` (`net462`) — MSTest v3 requires at minimum .NET Framework 4.6.2, so this should still be supported. Actually, let me think again. \n\nMSTest v3 supports .NET Framework 4.6.2 and above, .NET 6.0 and above, and .NET Standard 2.0. The test adapter and runner might have different requirements though. Looking at the actual compatibility for MSTest v3 — it supports .NET Framework 4.6.2+, .NET 6.0+, but dropped support for .NET Core 3.1 and .NET 5.0.\n\nSo the user's project will run into problems with `netcoreapp3.1` and `net5.0` since MSTest v3 doesn't support those runtimes, while `net462` should work fine. MSTest v3 also consolidates the packages into a single `MSTest` reference instead of separate `MSTest.TestFramework` and `MSTest.TestAdapter` packages, though the separate ones still work. There are other breaking changes like API removals and `TestContext` modifications, but the TFM compatibility is the main blocker here.","outputTokens":768,"requestId":"67CD:2636C7:31741D1:36A1FE2:69FD5066"},"id":"28eb43b2-f1c8-4527-8ae1-526b0b256f4c","timestamp":"2026-05-08T02:54:46.013Z","parentId":"7a7f9d35-f3bb-4389-a1e4-4b3d5f4dad41"}
